"1455","1420":"1420","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1360–":"omkring 1360–Afdød","1360–Female":"1360–Afdød","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1360–Male":"1360–Afdød","about 1360":"omkring 1360","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"nl":{"about 1360–":"circa 1360–Overleden","1360–Female":"1360–Overleden","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1360–Male":"1360–Overleden","about 1360":"circa 1360","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"about 1360–":"about 1360–Deceased","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","about 1360":"about 1360","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shaw","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): from Middle English <i>s(c)hawe</i>, <i>s(c)haghe</i> ‘small wood, grove, thicket’ (Old English <i>sceaga</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a small wood, or habitational, for someone from any of the many places so named. <i>Shaw</i> and <i>Shawe</i> are most frequent in Lancashire and Yorkshire, where Shaw in Oldham (Lancashire) may be a principal source of the surname. The English and Lowland Scottish surname was also established in Ireland in the 17th century.","Scottish: shortened form of various surnames from the Gaelic personal name <i>Sitheach</i>, derived from <i>sithech</i> ‘wolf’.","Irish (Down and Antrim): adopted for <b>Ó Síthigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a personal name based on <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’. Compare   Sheehy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Show","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cumberland): probably a variant of   Shaw  , perhaps representing a blend in Middle English of Old English <i>sceaga</i> and Old Norse <i>skógr</i>, both meaning ‘wood’.","Perhaps an Americanized form of German   Schau  ."]},{"name":"Sheehy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Aisling, Brigid, Declan, Egan, Eoin, Finbar, Ronan.","Irish (Limerick and Kerry): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Síthigh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, or <b>Mac Síthigh</b> ‘son of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a form of the Irish personal name <i>Síodhach</i> ‘peaceful’, from the adjective <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’ or ‘other worldly’ (see   Sheehan  ). The noun <i>síth</i>, from which this adjective derives, means basically ‘settlement’, hence both ‘peace’ and ‘place inhabited by other world beings’. This name was established in Ireland from the early 14th century, when a branch of the Scottish McDonnells, descended from <i>Sítheach</i>, great-grandson of Domhnaill, settled in the country."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":95,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],